# Echothink-Patch: 0008-request-proof-helper
# Title: Build and sign canonical request-proof payloads natively
# Area: extension-device-bridge / request-proof
# Depends-On: echothink/0007-device-identity.patch, echothink/0024-narrow-extension-bridge.patch
# Spec-Depends-On: docs/echothink-browser-alpha/t25-define-request-proof-payload-and-allowlist.md, docs/echothink-browser-alpha/t26-implement-proof-signing-helper.md
# Browser-Layer-Reason: The browser owns the local device private key and is the only place that can build a trustworthy canonical description of an outbound Echothink request and sign it. T24 exposed a narrow bridge that signed an opaque caller string; T25 requires the final Alpha contract to validate structured request fields, enforce an exact Echothink signing allowlist, and construct the canonical bytes in native code before signing. Backend/gateway services still own enrollment binding, authorization, replay protection, and proof validation.
# Preferred-Surface-Checked: extension, native-required (the canonicalization, allowlist enforcement, and signing must run in browser-owned native code because the device private key never leaves the browser; the JavaScript bridge cannot be trusted to canonicalize the signed bytes)
# Security-Critical-Areas: none (no network stack, TLS validation, sandbox, renderer internals, downloads, history, bookmarks, password manager, cookies, or DevTools changes; the request is described and signed, never fetched)
# Native-Files-Touched: chrome/browser/extensions/api/echothink_device/BUILD.gn, chrome/browser/extensions/api/echothink_device/echothink_request_proof.h (new), chrome/browser/extensions/api/echothink_device/echothink_request_proof.cc (new), chrome/browser/extensions/api/echothink_device/echothink_device_api.cc, chrome/common/extensions/api/echothink_device.idl
# Rebase-Risk: low (changes are confined to the Echothink device-bridge extension API added by echothink/0024; reuses the existing SignProofPayload native entry point added there and only adds a self-contained canonicalizer plus //url dep)
# Validation: Apply inherited patches and active Echothink predecessors through echothink/0024-narrow-extension-bridge.patch, then this patch with `patch -p1` against pinned Chromium 148.0.7778.178. Build on Windows and verify that the bundled extension lokdibgfmiemhdoogailbfpdggndpolk can call chrome.echothinkDevice.signProofPayload({method,url,timestamp[,nonce][,access_token_hash]}) for an allowlisted https://api.echothink.ai/v1/, https://auth.echothink.ai/browser/, https://auth.echothink.ai/device/, or https://app.echothink.ai/api/ destination and receives {ok:true, proof_type:"echothink-request-proof-v1", proof, key_id, key_algorithm:"ES256", timestamp}; that malformed payloads return {ok:false, error:"invalid_payload"}; that third-party hosts, sibling subdomains, http/file/chrome/echo URLs, userinfo, non-default ports, IP literals, localhost, search.echothink.ai, and updates.echothink.ai return {ok:false, error:"disallowed_destination"} before any signature is produced; and that no result, error, log, or crash key ever contains the private key, DPAPI blob, raw access token, canonical payload bytes, or a separate signature value.
#
# Notes:
# - This patch replaces the T24 opaque-string signing surface with the T25
#   canonical request-proof contract. The extension now passes structured
#   request fields; native code validates them, enforces the Echothink signing
#   allowlist, builds the canonical UTF-8 JSON in the fixed field order
#   (method, url, timestamp, nonce, access_token_hash), and only then signs the
#   canonical bytes with the device key via the existing SignProofPayload entry
#   point from echothink/0024.
# - The canonical JSON is built by hand (not base::Value::Dict) because Dict
#   serialization sorts keys; the field order is contractual.
# - The returned proof is opaque and header-ready for T27: it is
#   base64url(canonical_json) + "." + base64url(DER ECDSA-SHA256 signature).
#   The helper no longer returns the bare signature or canonical bytes as
#   separate fields.
# - The browser does not store replay caches, nonce history, proof history,
#   signatures, or tokens. Backend/gateway services own replay protection and
#   proof verification. The extension manifest and host permissions are
#   unchanged; no webRequest, native messaging, cookies, or DevTools surface is
#   added.

